			<div class="post-347 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-census-data category-demographics-2">
				<!-- title, meta, and date info -->
				<div class="title clearfix">
					<div class="post-title">
						<h3 id="post-347"><a href="http://demographicsgoldmine.com/who-are-our-veterans-a-look-at-the-most-recent-numbers-on-veterans-of-america">Who Are Our Veterans?  A Look at the Most Recent Numbers on Veterans of America.</a></h3>
					</div>
					
					<div class="author-meta">
						by <span class="meta-author"><a href="http://demographicsgoldmine.com/author/Bob Scardamalia" title="Bob Scardamalia">Bob Scardamalia</a></span>					</div>
					
					<div class="post-meta">
						<span class="month">November</span>
						<span class="day">11<span class="day-suffix">th</span><span class="day-comma">,</span></span>
						<span class="year">2012</span><br />
					</div>
					</div>
				
				<!-- "Read More" link -->
				<div class="post-content">
					<p>I was a lucky one.  When I was in college in the early 70’s, my draft number was 18.  I graduated in 1973 shortly after the end of the Vietnam War so my number was never called and I never had to serve.   I was a lucky one.  </p>
<p><img src="http://demographicsgoldmine.com/images/veteransday2012.jpg" style="float:right; margin:10px">Many of that time weren’t so lucky, they served, many died and even those returning home were never the same.  See, we didn’t look at or honor our veterans of that time period the way we do today.  It’s such a good thing that we’ve grown up to better understand the sacrifices those men and women made and are still making today.  </p>
<p>So it’s time to honor them and to do so we need to understand who they are.  The Census Bureau provides a lot of information to profile our veterans.   Here are some recent stats from the 2011 American Community Survey&#8230;</p>
<p>• &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There are 21.5 million military veterans in the U.S. and 1.6 million are women.<br />
• &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Persons of all races and ethnic groups serve our nation: 2.3 million Blacks; 1.2 million Hispanics; 265,000 Asians; 153,000 American Indian or Alaska Native; 27,000 Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander; and 17.2 million non-Hispanic Whites.<br />
• &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;9.2 million vets are 65 and older while 1.8 million are under 35.<br />
• &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There are 7.5 million Vietnam era veterans; 5.1 million served during the Gulf Wars (from August 1990 to present); 1.8 million serving from World War II and 2.4 million from the Korean War.  Those serving in peacetime only numbered 5.4 million.<br />
• &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I didn’t know that veteran’s disabilities are rated on a scale from 1 to 100 to determine their eligibility for compensation.  3.5 million vets have a service connected disability rating and 810,000 have a rating of 70 or higher!  </p>
<p>We all know someone who has served – family, friends, loved ones, distant relations.  We know them individually and personally.  Sometimes it’s helpful to recognize and say thank you to our veterans as the collective whole who have sacrificed for this country.  Thank you.</p>
				</div>
				
				<!-- categories, tags and comments -->
				<div class="meta-bottom clearfix">
					<div class="alignleft"><span class="categories">Categories <a href="http://demographicsgoldmine.com/category/census-data" title="View all posts in Census Data" rel="category tag">Census Data</a>, <a href="http://demographicsgoldmine.com/category/demographics-2" title="View all posts in Demographics" rel="category tag">Demographics</a></span><br />
